          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Haiti gang massacre</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">Gang members have <a href="https://english.elpais.com/international/2024-12-10/terror-massacre-and-voodoo-in-the-latest-episode-of-gang-violence-in-haiti.html" target="_blank">murdered</a> at least 180 elderly people in the Haitian capital of Port-au-Prince. The killings were instigated by a local gang leader whose son fell ill and died. After consulting a voodoo priest, he blamed elderly people practicing “witchcraft” were responsible for the boy’s illness. In retaliation, gang members rounded up residents aged over 60 from their homes and murdered them in the streets.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          Recent months have seen a <a href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2024/10/30/haitis-gangs-inflict-extreme-brutality-as-casualties-rise-un-report" target="_blank">surge</a> in gang attacks on ordinary residents in Haiti, following a brief decline earlier this year due to a temporary truce. Gangs <a href="https://www.voanews.com/a/un-haitian-children-account-for-about-half-of-country-s-armed-gang-members-/7884775.html" target="_blank">control</a> around 85% of Port-au-Prince and many rural areas, displacing over 700,000 Haitians, including half a million children. This is not the first act of violence linked to religion; in 2021, the gang killed 12 women, accusing them of following witchcraft.</p>
        </mj-text>
